look for counties with similar traits. characteristics and saturation rates and apply Lumina's cost structure to these counties.  As an added bonus adjust GM per mile of extra drive time.

Creating a detailed spreadsheet report with the metrics specified involves generating and organizing a lot of data. Here is a conceptual framework of how the spreadsheet could look, populated with made-up numbers to illustrate the structure:

### Summary Report Breakdown by Metro Area

**Metrics:**
1. Number of Leads
2. Conversion Rate of Leads
3. Number of Opportunities
4. Closed Categories by Percentage by Metro Area
5. Closed Won
6. Number of Closed Won
7. Type of Financing
8. Average Deal Size (kW and $$)
9. Average GM per Deal (% and/or $)
10. % of Overall Installs in Municipality (Market Share)
11. Lumina System Sizes Compared to Average
12. Financing Types Compared by Average
13. Average System Size, Price, and GM per Financing Type
14. Closed/Lost
15. Breakdown by Municipality
16. Competitor Analysis
17. Census Data Analysis (Income, GM in Richer vs. Less Affluent Areas)
18. Customer Acquisition Cost per County per Deal Type
19. $/Watt Marketing to $/Watt Installed, $/Watt GM
20. Impact of Increased Marketing Spend on Market Share
21. County Comparison with Similar Traits

### Example Data

Here’s an example of how this data could be structured in a spreadsheet format:

#### Metro Area Summary

| Metro Area      | Leads | Conversion Rate | Opportunities | Closed Categories (%) | Closed Won | Type of Financing  | Avg Deal Size (kW) | Avg Deal Size ($) | Avg GM per Deal ($) | Market Share (%) | Lumina Avg System Size (kW) | Avg System Size (kW) | Avg Price ($) | GM (%) |
|-----------------|-------|-----------------|---------------|-----------------------|------------|---------------------|--------------------|-------------------|---------------------|------------------|-----------------------------|----------------------|---------------|-------|
| Metro Area 1    | 1000  | 10%             | 100           | 50%                   | 50         | Loan, Lease, PPA    | 10                 | 50,000            | 15,000              | 25%              | 10                          | 8                    | 40,000        | 30%   |
| Metro Area 2    | 1500  | 12%             | 180           | 45%                   | 81         | Cash, Loan, Lease   | 12                 | 60,000            | 18,000              | 30%              | 12                          | 10                   | 55,000        | 33%   |
| Metro Area 3    | 800   | 15%             | 120           | 60%                   | 72         | PPA, Loan           | 9                  | 45,000            | 13,500              | 20%              | 9                           | 7                    | 38,000        | 28%   |

#### Financing Type Breakdown

| Financing Type  | Avg System Size (kW) | Avg Price ($) | Avg GM ($) | % of Deals |
|-----------------|----------------------|---------------|------------|------------|
| Cash            | 12                   | 60,000        | 18,000     | 30%        |
| Loan            | 10                   | 50,000        | 15,000     | 50%        |
| Lease           | 11                   | 55,000        | 16,500     | 15%        |
| PPA             | 9                    | 45,000        | 13,500     | 5%         |

#### Closed/Lost Breakdown by Municipality

| Municipality     | Closed Won | Closed Lost | Competitor Losses | Total Installs | Lumina Market Share (%) |
|------------------|------------|-------------|--------------------|----------------|-------------------------|
| Municipality 1   | 50         | 30          | 20                 | 100            | 50%                     |
| Municipality 2   | 80         | 40          | 60                 | 180            | 44%                     |
| Municipality 3   | 40         | 20          | 40                 | 100            | 40%                     |

| County           | Customer Acquisition Cost ($) | $/Watt Marketing | $/Watt Installed | $/Watt GM | Increase in Market Share (%) | Historical Yield ($) |
|------------------|-------------------------------|------------------|------------------|-----------|------------------------------|-----------------------|

# Creating a DataFrame for the summary report
data = {
    "Metric": [
        "Number of Leads",
        "Conversion Rate of Leads",
        "Number of Opportunities",
        "Closed Categories by Percentage by Metro Area",
        "Closed Won",
        "Number of Closed Won",
        "Type of Financing",
        "Average Deal Size (kW)",
        "Average Deal Size ($)",
        "Average GM per Deal ($)",
        "% of Overall Installs in Municipality (Market Share)",
        "Lumina System Sizes Compared to Average",
        "Average System Size (kW)",
        "Average Price ($)",
        "Average GM (%)"
    ],
    "Metro Area 1": [1000, "10%", 100, "50%", 50, 50, "Loan, Lease, PPA", 10, 50000, 15000, "25%", 10, 8, 40000, "30%"],
    "Metro Area 2": [1500, "12%", 180, "45%", 81, 81, "Cash, Loan, Lease", 12, 60000, 18000, "30%", 12, 10, 55000, "33%"],
    "Metro Area 3": [800, "15%", 120, "60%", 72, 72, "PPA, Loan", 9, 45000, 13500, "20%", 9, 7, 38000, "28%"]
}

summary_df = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Creating a DataFrame for financing type breakdown
financing_data = {
    "Financing Type": ["Cash", "Loan", "Lease", "PPA"],
    "Average System Size (kW)": [12, 10, 11, 9],
    "Average Price ($)": [60000, 50000, 55000, 45000],
    "Average GM ($)": [18000, 15000, 16500, 13500],
    "% of Deals": ["30%", "50%", "15%", "5%"]
}

financing_df = pd.DataFrame(financing_data)

# Creating a DataFrame for closed/lost breakdown by municipality
closed_lost_data = {
    "Municipality": ["Municipality 1", "Municipality 2", "Municipality 3"],
    "Closed Won": [50, 80, 40],
    "Closed Lost": [30, 40, 20],
    "Competitor Losses": [20, 60, 40],
    "Total Installs": [100, 180, 100],
    "Lumina Market Share (%)": ["50%", "44%", "40%"]
}

closed_lost_df = pd.DataFrame(closed_lost_data)

# Creating a DataFrame for census data and GM analysis
census_data = {
    "County": ["County 1", "County 2", "County 3"],
    "Median Household Income": [80000, 100000, 60000],
    "GM in Richer Areas ($)": [18000, 20000, 15000],
    "GM in Less Affluent Areas ($)": [15000, 14000, 13000]
}

census_df = pd.DataFrame(census_data)

# Creating a DataFrame for customer acquisition and marketing analysis
acquisition_data = {
    "County": ["County 1", "County 2", "County 3"],
    "Customer Acquisition Cost ($)": [1000, 1200, 800],
    "$/Watt Marketing": [0.5, 0.6, 0.4],
    "$/Watt Installed": [3, 3.5, 2.8],
    "$/Watt GM": [1, 1.2, 0.9],
    "Increase in Market Share (%)": ["10%", "15%", "8%"],
    "Historical Yield ($)": [100000, 120000, 80000]
}

acquisition_df = pd.DataFrame(acquisition_data)

# Creating an Excel writer object and writing the DataFrames to separate sheets
excel_writer = pd.ExcelWriter('/mnt/data/solar_sales_report.xlsx', engine='xlsxwriter')

summary_df.to_excel(excel_writer, sheet_name='Metro Area Summary', index=False)
financing_df.to_excel(excel_writer, sheet_name='Financing Breakdown', index=False)
closed_lost_df.to_excel(excel_writer, sheet_name='Closed Lost Breakdown', index=False)
census_df.to_excel(excel_writer, sheet_name='Census Data Analysis', index=False)
acquisition_df.to_excel(excel_writer, sheet_name='Customer Acquisition', index=False)

# Save the Excel file
excel_writer.save()

# File path for the saved Excel file
file_path = '/mnt/data/solar_sales_report.xlsx'
file_path
